column156: Before COVID, I was very physically active. Probably the most fit I've ever been in my life. However since school has closed and the hours of doing sports per week have died down (eventually ending), I've become pretty unfit pretty fast. Now that school and hockey are still not really happening, I've lost all motivation and can't bring myself to do exercise.
column157: YES. A pond by my house just recently froze over and so I just recently began going down and skating on it a few times this week. It's more of an escape and a way to kind of numb my mind tbh.
column158: I feel alone. My friends and I were just starting to find time to hang out and do stuff outside of school before lockdown. We haven't really been talking at all over the past six months. So I just feel really lonely. Not just with friends, but with human interaction in general. I've barely spoken to anyone outside my household over the past six months, and although I consider myself an introvert, I find myself longing to talk and/or hangout with someone. Anyone. Also my motivation for school dropped, which is pretty bad considering the fact that I'm in grade 12. But since I'm spending all my time at home, I've been skipping the occasional class now and then (something I NEVER did before). I honestly feel little motivation. That, and online school sucks. The way it is run makes it difficult to communicate with the teacher and learn the content (at least for me). In summary, I just feel very sad, alone, unmotivated, and useless. Also I didn't mean to write this much. Sorry!

column158: Lockdown has left a lot of time for self reflection, so I've discovered new career paths and the feeling of loneliness and loss during lockdown.  I have definitely grown as a person during quarantine, especially since it is during the more formative years of our lives and said to be the most entertaining. I have gained a deeper understanding for people who have experienced the harsher realities of covid and lockdown, while some can go vacationing in the Caribbean, I couldn't see my grandpa for the last time and that made me realize a lot about society and what my family means to me, it has become more important to cherish what's there.

column156: I have given myself a lot more to do over the lockdown and the focus of those extracurriculars has definitely changed. It's more leadership-related and it takes a lot more initiative. I spend the bulk of my time completing schoolwork and keeping up with extracurriculars, which in turn means that I have less time for my other interests. However, I have found that with the full lockdown, I get some of this time back because school cools down a little. I'm able to film and edit small projects or draw just for fun.
column157: As someone who doesn't enjoy an abundance of social interaction, I, selfishly, found lockdown very easy and rewarding at the beginning. I never missed others, my grades were thriving, my mental health was at an all-time high. However, when summer came and restrictions eased up, I was able to meet my friends (with masks, gloves, sanitizer, distancing, etc.) and gain back some of the social interaction that I lost. This was until Halloween, which was when things started quickly deteriorating. We weren't meeting anymore to keep ourselves and our immunocompromised family members safe; back at square one. I think having that minimal sense of normalcy triggered something because I've started desperately wanting it back. I want to see my friends, have picnics, all the normal teenage things I've suddenly realized I don't and won't have. Very strange, but super new and different from the rest of lockdown.
column158: On the one hand, I feel so unhappy and cheated to lose the experiences I so desperately long for: dances, assemblies, spirit weeks, club meetings, etc. I wonder whether I'll ever get those experiences that you remember for the rest of your life, even the bad prom dresses and horrible dance songs. However, I'm also appreciative of my family members' good health and the quality time that I get with my immediate family. I'll be gone at university at some point, so being able to spend time with my dog and my parents is a privilege. It's a balance of both, which is what I've learned from my privileged lockdown experience.

column158: i think the HWDSB has done a GODAWFUL job at the online "adaptive learning". it hasn't benefitted me in any way. all it has done is added more stress to my every day life and makes me dread getting up in the morning. im struggling to do the most basic tasks and every day is just suffering trying my best to get by doing the bare minimum. i used to excel in my classes and be hopeful for doing school work, now i dont care as long as i pass my classes. my mind is always clouded and i cant think straight anymore. everything is so overwhelming and the HWDSB has done nothing but make it worse. its gotten to the point where i consider dropping out but i cant because i dont have a job and my parents would hate me. the HWDSB is treating this like a vacation meanwhile we're living in what i can only describe as hell. every day is the same, wake up, stress about classes, wonder if im gonna fail or not, stress here, stress there, cant think about anything except for stress and school. its purgatory. i dont want to keep living like this. im barely scraping by and i dont know how much longer i can take it. the lack of support from the HWDSB is astonishing because they talk so highly of themselves saying "we're here for you" and "we know these are difficult times" yet they're the main reason why the times are difficult. i almost dont know who i am anymore because i think about how (slightly) happy i used to be and how good i used to be in school, and now i wake up every day wishing i could go back to sleep and never wake up, barely passing my classes just showing up to meetings to learn absolutely NOTHING. the only thing thats keeping me sane and keeping my mental state from slipping over the edge is my girlfriend, and i cant even see her because of the stay at home order. im living solely off of the hopes that i can maybe see her again soon. nothing else in my life is worth it. i spend my days away playing video games to distract myself from the nightmare that is this world. i dont feel real anymore. i wake up at 10am and next thing you know its 9pm in a span that feels like 20 minutes. life is nothing but anxiety and dread. im in a constant state of depression to the point that i want to give up on everything but i cant because i have to live up to my parents expectations. its a neverending cycle of just pain. i hope someone actually takes the time to read this as long as it is because its genuinely how i feel and i cant keep living like this. there's nothing thats helping me at all, therapy doesnt help, my parents only make it worse, i cant find a job so i dont have any money to occupy myself and keep myself busy. there is no joy in this life except for one other human being that im not allowed to see.

column156: I play on a volleyball team so while things were still sort of open, I had 3+ practices a week. Now, with everything being shut down again, I no longer have volleyball practices. My club has set up 2 zoom calls a week to workout but it is very different. Because I don't have practices, I spend a lot more time lying around, watching YouTube or TikTok. However, because of the lockdown, my older sister is living with us again which has allowed me to workout with her basically everyday. So, I may have lost some exercise through sports but I gained it back through working out.
column157: Only the fact that I no longer have volleyball practices. I don't have a lot of friends so the only time I hang out with other kids my age for fun is at my volleyball practices.
column158: I feel that I haven't really changed at all. I never went out to hang out with friends before the lockdown, and I still don't so nothing has changed. I think I have gotten closer to my siblings since everyone is living at home now. We also got a puppy (our third dog in the household) so that was a fun experience. In terms of school, I have been getting similar, if not better grades than usual. Really the only major change for me because of the lockdown was losing my volleyball practices which does suck however, I know that this is insignificant compared to what other people have lost from the lockdown.

column158: My dad, he is an anesthesiologist. Iäó»ve always been proud of him and what he does, but since the pandemic, Iäó»ve appreciate what he does more and how hard he works. Due to the new COVID-19 protocols, he has to wear lots of PPE on top of the regular greens that he wears on top of his clothes. This PPE includes, extra pairs of gloves, an N-95 mask and a face shield on top of it, an extra gown, boot and neck covers. When he does extensive cases such as open heart for example, he has to wear all of these extra layers for up to 12 hours at a time. I can only imagine how hot he must get. When he comes home after a long shift, I try my best to be on good behaviour and help my mom make a meal so that he can eat and relax. He never complains about his job even if he had a hard day and I am really thankful for everything that he does for me and my family. Since covid-19 started, I now feel a little more worried when he leaves to work, because I know that he deals with patients who have it and I really donäó»t want him to get it and become ill. Iäó»m sure that lots of other family how either are or have frontline workers in their household feel the same and I appreciate everything they do. I feel like the City of Hamilton should do more to acknowledge them.
